bOyUR1Q6chOgN63UzJ4cQm-_ZlRqp9H2Vra4WKp6196nrKJuEMk66r0K3o9UdOUaWSOEGKi7j9-YfTpg4VRxAZgATsK851V-SFgexO3IMr_52Ns6WvzOGsvP6XTGY5Ve-2rxURvYxZJh1VMuanwo=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating test assertions**\\n\\nI’m considering how to handle line 42 catch and success. I think I can run the test without using the `__intercept`. This way, my assertions will be simpler. I can use `Category.describe` with `bean.as().getName` without any replacement since there won’t be an intercept involved. My expected outcome in this case would be \\\"hello Ada.\\\" It feels like a straightforward approach, which is nice! Let's see how this works out.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating BaseProxyCategory usage**\\n\\nI'm considering whether line 94 would invoke BaseProxyCategory for `bean.as().getName()` within the describe function and if it remains unchanged. I’m pondering its safety and whether it uses a public class from the library request factory. It's tricky since the user mentioned accessing the internal library, which complicates things. I need to focus on the active class. There's a tension between using the existing library category and ensuring version agnosticism. However, integrating the BaseProxyCategory might still be a viable option.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying tests and metadata**\\n\\nI'm trying to figure out if it's okay to use test classes with reflection in this TCK. It seems like many tests do this, but I wonder if the reachability metadata should actually exclude user test classes. I think it would be worthwhile to inspect the generated metadata for GWT to better understand this, as it might clarify whether the inclusion of user test classes is appropriate or not. There’s a lot to consider!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_DG0rvy6e7aKV2Uti94z8mjzq|fc_056430e4759d3fca0169f55c044b10819e924efd8cd3655602", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find metadata/org.gwtproject/gwt-user